Here's a basic media query for mobile devices:

## Basic Mobile Media Query

```css
/* Mobile styles */
@media screen and (max-width: 768px) {
  /* Your mobile styles here */
  body {
    font-size: 14px;
    padding: 10px;
  }

  .container {
    width: 100%;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .navigation {
    display: block;
  }
}
```

## More Specific Mobile Breakpoints

```css
/* Small mobile devices (phones, 0px to 480px) */
@media screen and (max-width: 480px) {
  /* Styles for small phones */
}

/* Medium mobile devices (large phones, 481px to 768px) */
@media screen and (min-width: 481px) and (max-width: 768px) {
  /* Styles for larger phones/small tablets */
}

/* Alternative: Mobile-first approach */
@media screen and (min-width: 320px) {
  /* Base mobile styles */
}

@media screen and (min-width: 768px) {
  /* Tablet and desktop styles */
}
```

## Complete Responsive Breakpoint System

```css
/* Mobile First Approach */

/* Extra small devices (phones, less than 576px) */
@media screen and (max-width: 575.98px) {
  .container {
    padding: 0 15px;
  }
}

/* Small devices (landscape phones, 576px and up) */
@media screen and (min-width: 576px) {
  .container {
    max-width: 540px;
  }
}

/* Medium devices (tablets, 768px and up) */
@media screen and (min-width: 768px) {
  .container {
    max-width: 720px;
  }
}

/* Large devices (desktops, 992px and up) */
@media screen and (min-width: 992px) {
  .container {
    max-width: 960px;
  }
}
```

The most commonly used mobile breakpoint is `@media screen and (max-width: 768px)` which targets most mobile devices.
